x;"><strong>Chuck Schumer</strong>, the typically jovial Senate Democratic =
leader, has
always prided himself on his vintage flip phone and preternatural ability t=
o remember colleagues=E2=80=99 numbers. Lately, however, Schumer hasn=E2=80=
=99t been rolling calls with the urgency that his caucus has come to expect=
=2E Indeed, as Senate Democrats stare d=
own the barrel of their first conseque=
ntial vote, I=E2=80=99m told Schumer is as torn and demoralized as the rest=
 of his party. <br/><br/>Democrats, of course, have vanishingly little powe=
r in Washington these days. One of their fleetingly few points of leverage
is the upcoming Senate vote on the Republican bill to fund the government, =
which passed the House on Tuesday despite near-unified opposition from thei=
r party brethren. Its fate now falls to Senate Democrats, at least eight of=
 whom would need to provide the votes to overcome a filibuster. Based on my=
 conversations on the Hill this week, it=E2=80=99s clear that many of them =
fear being held responsible for a potential government shutdown. At the sam=
e time, however, they=E2=80=99re feeling immense pressure from
their angry-as-hell constituents to do<em> something</em> about <strong>Don=
ald Trump</strong> and <strong>Elon Musk</strong>=E2=80=99s wrecking-ball-s=
tyle demolition of the federal government, and about looming Republican bud=
get cuts that could impact essential programs like Social Security and Medi=
caid=E2=80=94Trump=E2=80=99s insistence to the contrary notwithstanding.</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>In short, it=E2=80=99s the kind of moment that=
 party leaders are made for. Particularly someone like Schumer, who boasts =
of being
in constant contact with his members, weighing their concerns and moods, he=
lping craft strategy=E2=80=94even if members and staff sometimes complain t=
hat he=E2=80=99s afraid to play hardball and often defaults to telling memb=
ers what they want to hear. But these days he doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be te=
lling members much of anything, other than to keep their powder dry and the=
ir mouths shut as reporters probe his proclamation that his caucus is unifi=
ed. (It=E2=80=99s not.)</p></div>
