x;">Ahead of a two-hour, closed-door caucus meeting on Tuesday, members exp=
ected to get some
answers about how they should vote, and how they should <em>message</em> th=
eir votes. Instead, I=E2=80=99m told, they got a grievance-filled brainstor=
ming session in which Schumer did a lot of=E2=80=A6 <em>listening</em>. The=
 meeting ended without a unified message or plan. =E2=80=9CComplete lack of=
 leadership,=E2=80=9D one Democratic aide said. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s no=
 sense of direction.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As early as last week, I=
 began hearing Democrats grumble
that Schumer was keeping his cards <em>too</em> close to the vest and offer=
ing little insight into his thought process on the funding bill. In hindsig=
ht, perhaps, he had no cards to show. Democrats are frustrated that Schumer=
 didn=E2=80=99t ready an aggressive plan to tear apart and criticize the Ho=
use Republican bill. He didn=E2=80=99t threaten Senate Majority Leader <str=
ong>John Thune</strong> and his conference with consequences in private, le=
t alone in public.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Instead, Democrats
have told me, Schumer=E2=80=99s strategy ahead of the House vote seemed to =
be to pray that Speaker <strong>Mike Johnson</strong> couldn=E2=80=99t coal=
esce his usually divisive Republican conference to pass a government spendi=
ng bill. When asked what he was telling his members at his weekly news conf=
erence on Tuesday=E2=80=94by which point much of the reporting had made cle=
ar that the House would pass the bill=E2=80=94Schumer spent barely five sec=
onds saying he=E2=80=99d =E2=80=9Cwait and see what the House does,=E2=80=
=9D before moving on quickly. He
apparently didn=E2=80=99t want to believe that the House could fall in line=
, not because of a Johnson masterstroke, but because of G.O.P. fealty to Tr=
ump. Now, funding the government is the Senate=E2=80=99s problem.</p></div>
