re having to weigh the anger from their animated base against the knowledge=
 that any short-term gain of sticking it to Trump could lead to long-term h=
avoc.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On the other hand, if they vote for Republ=
icans=E2=80=99 funding bill, Democrats are well aware they=E2=80=99ll be ba=
sically offering up a =E2=80=9Cslush fund=E2=80=9D to Trump with few guardr=
ails on how
he can spend the money. They worry that if they don=E2=80=99t take a stand =
now, then Republicans will continue to roll them at every turn. Senate Demo=
crats are also under pressure from their House counterparts after Minority =
Leader <strong>Hakeem Jeffries</strong> managed to keep his caucus united i=
n opposition to the bill in the House. =E2=80=9CIf not now, when? If not us=
, then who?=E2=80=9D California Rep. <strong>Scott Peters</strong> said in =
a statement. (Arguably, House Democrats had an easier time holding the
line since they could not, by themselves, tank the bill; the dynamics are d=
ifferent in the Senate, where the filibuster prevails.)<br/><br/>Schumer in=
sists his caucus is unified, too, at least on a short-term funding alternat=
ive. During another day of closed-door discussions, he told Senate Democrat=
s that the eight Democratic votes necessary to fund the government aren=E2=
=80=99t there, and he made the same pronouncement on the floor. (Senator <s=
trong>Rand Paul</strong> has already said he=E2=80=99ll vote against
it, which is why Republicans need eight Democrats to advance the bill.) But=
 based on my discussions with Democrats, they aren=E2=80=99t unified on wha=
t to do about the vote they <em>actually</em> face. In fact, they=E2=80=99r=
e not unified in their <em>predictions</em> of how many of them will vote f=
or the funding bill=E2=80=94some think there are more than eight =E2=80=9Cy=
ea=E2=80=9D votes to fund the government in their midst. Schumer could just=
 be trying to instill fear in Republicans, who are also a bit nervous about=
 how this will
all play out, but if there=E2=80=99s a bigger strategy here, it=E2=80=99s a=
 headscratcher.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">One Democratic strategist posited to me=
 last week that Senate Democrats would thread the needle, providing the mem=
bers needed to get past the 60-vote threshold in the procedural votes befor=
e voting against actual passage of the bill, which requires only a simple m=
ajority=E2=80=94an old-school tactic that lets members claim not to have
obstructed <em>process</em> even as they opposed the underlying <em>legisla=
tion</em>. But as the public, especially the activated base, understands Se=
nate procedure more than most, it=E2=80=99s a hard needle to thread.=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
">There=E2=80=99s an old adage on Capitol Hill that it=E2=80=99s easier to =
lead in the minority, when the party out of power has no ability to pass it=
s agenda. But Schumer=E2=80=99s performance on funding is giving Democrats =
the worst
of all governing worlds: They have no power, and, apparently, no leadership=
 either.</p></div>
